title: For Sale:  Mossberg 930 Semi-Auto 12 ga Shotgun
postcontent:
I have for sale a very good condition Mossberg 930 Slugster.  This shotgun is 12 gauge and has a rifled barrel for shooting Sabot slugs.  If you want to use it for home defense or bird hunting, just pick up another barrel and swap it out.  This was my deer hunting gun last year but this year I now have a .44 Magnum rifle so I no longer need this.  It functions flawlessly.  It has a 24" ported barrel for reduced muzzle rise and holds 4+1 without the plug and 2+1 with the plug installed.  I have upgraded the magazine spring to a higher powered Wolff spring and upgraded the follower to a GG&G steel/aluminum follower for more reliable feeding.  The barrel has an integrated cantilever scope base ready to mount a scope of your choice.  The stock is a monte carlo style and is polymer.  I have also added a shell holder on the stock to carry an extra 5 shells.  This shotgun will shoot 2 3/4" and 3" shells.  It has a spacer system to adjust the drop angle of the stock.  It also has a quick empty button that will release all of the loaded shells with the press of the button.  I have the original box, owner's manual, lock, the stock magazine spring and magazine follower, as well as an extra recoil pad and a Limbsaver recoil pad.  I am also including 3 boxes of Sabot slugs to get you started.  I had this out hunting 1 day last year and dropped a deer in its tracks with it at 60 yards.  This is a great deer gun, I just no longer need it.

Asking $500 for everything.  Located in the Dublin/Hilliard area of Northwest Columbus.  NOT interested in trades at this time.  Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale/Trade:  stainless  Savage Model 93R17
postcontent:
I have for sale here locally in West Pensacola...... I am asking 340 obo...... here are links to this rifle on the internet.

I feel the price is pretty fair.

FOR SALE ON BUDS http://www.budsgunshop.com/catalog/product_info.php/products_id/24246

Gander Mtn. Savage Model 93 R17 BTVS Rimfire Rifle http://www.gandermountain.com/modperl/product/details.cgi?i=GM416262

Comes with a box plus of ammo


REVIEW ChuckHawk Review The Savage Arms Model 93R series represents the Savage bolt action entry in the great rimfire rifle sweepstakes. The 93R17 series is chambered exclusively for the .17 HMR cartridge. These rifles represent the pinnacle of rimfire performance as interpreted by Savage Arms.

I have written extensively about the .17 HMR cartridge elsewhere on the Rimfire Guns and Ammo Page, so I will not repeat the whole story here. It is sufficient to say that with a 17 grain Hornady V-MAX bullet at a MV of 2550 fps, the .17 HMR is the flattest shooting, longest range rimfire cartridge on the market. It is the most accurate (factory loaded) small game and varmint cartridge I can remember testing. A good shot with a good rifle can usually shoot groups around 1.0 MOA at 100 yards. The precision with which .17 HMR ammo is manufactured is incredible!

The Savage 93R17 line of rifles is an extensive one. Included are models offering standard contour and heavy (varmint) barrels, and stocks of hardwood, laminated wood, black synthetic, and camo synthetic. Regardless of material, 93R17 series stocks come with detachable sling swivel bases.

All Model 93R17 rifles share the same basic Savage 93 action. This rear locking, cock on opening design features dual extractors and a fixed blade ejector. Cartridges are fed from a removable 5-round box magazine. The two-position safety (push forward for "fire") is located immediately behind the bolt handle at the right rear of the action. The "bottom iron" is blued sheet metal, and the trigger guard is plastic.

From 2006 onward all Savage Model 93R17 rifles have come with the Savage Accu-Trigger. This is the best rimfire rifle trigger that you will find short of the Olympics, and nothing else in the 93R17's price class even comes close.

It does not seem to fire currently, but the action, hammer, and trigger work. If nothing else, it should make a great parts gun.

The second is a Rohm RG14 .22LR. It works sometimes. Shoots decently when it does decide to work. Probably a pretty simple fix for someone that knows what to look for.

The third is in pretty rough shape. The timing would certainly need some work. A good bit of the finish is gone and it's friendly with the rust in some places. It says "U.S. Revolver Co." and "Made In USA" on it. Aside from the serial number I don't see any other markings on it. No idea of caliber, maybe .32 ??? Personally, I would not attempt to fire it in it's current condition. That said, you do what you want.

title: For Sale:  Rossi Revolver - .38 Special
postcontent:
My dad bought this revolver and a few years ago and enjoyed it until the firing pin broke.  It sat on his shelf for quite some time and he gave it to me last year since he never got around to fixing it.  I sent it back to Taurus and they replaced the firing pin and it works great now.  Unfortunately it's is too heavy for me to carry and I already have a full-sized pistol for home defense so I don't really have a use for it.  It is mechanically sound, and cosmetically in very good condition.  I would advise that if you want to practice dry firing you will need to buy snap-caps. With this older style of firing pin on the hammer you can break the tip off if you dry fire with nothing in the chamber.  That is probably what happened when it broke. You can see that hasn't seen much use, the bore is clean and shiny. It spent most of it's life in a safe.  Let me know if you have any questions.  Have a happy 4th of July and God bless.

**Note: I am only selling to FL residents with concealed carry permits, or military ID.  I'm all about 2A, but I also want to be sure this little guy goes to a good home.

title: For Sale:  Vintage/Rare - 60's 20rd M16 / AR15 Magazines
postcontent:
I am selling the last two remaining vintage/collector magazines in my collection.

I have a

$25 Simmonds - Army and late Air Force contract 20 round. Circa 1966 to 1971. Dull alloy followers. Central Industries -marked "Simmonds" on floor plate. This  is the same company that contracted and made Colt magazines. They are identical (trust me I had two I sold) except the floor plate! This magazine based on the spot weld is comparable to a late 68/69 colt mag I had. The wear on this is all natural, no chemical or forced wear and only comes with 50 years of regular use. This is the best mag for that "aged" look!

$25 Adventure Line - Army and late Air Force contract 20 round. Circa 1966 to 1971. Dull alloy followers. Colt contract marked "Adventure Line" on floorplate. Various sources say this was made for colt but branded as Adventure Line for the civilian market. Very early production due to quality of spot welds. Adventure Line was known to use a thicker anodizing and a thicker molly coating which lead to longer life and appearance as is visible in this This is the best condition mag, definitely a collector if you want a retro build that looks "new"! This has almost all the original finish (some wear by the mag catch).


The prices on these are fairly fixed as they either are on the market or not available at all. I am willing to discuss discounts if you want to buy both!

Please email me with any questions, I am located in the NW Valley near Norterra! I will not drive to meet you other than 5-10minutes. I will not ship nor accept trades.

postcontent:
This is indeed a Lew Horton Special Edition. This model was unique in the market place at that time, being chambered in .44 Magnum, having a three inch barrel and an unfluted cylinder.
It was shipped with rosewood grips. This gun is one of 1500 units produced. These Model 629’s were manufactured by Smith & Wesson and delivered to Lew Horton Distributing from 1997 to 2000. This gun was delivered to Lew Horton’s in April of 1999.
This Lew Horton Special Edition is listed in the Bluebook of Gun Values under the “Lew Horton Distributing” section.
I have the original box, ammo, holster and a letter from Lew Horton Distribution Company. 
This is a beautiful mint condition revolver.
